com.itko.lisa.coordinator

Interface TestRegistry

  • All Superinterfaces:
    com.itko.lisa.net.LisaServerObject, com.itko.lisa.coordinator.PersistentMap, ServiceManagerSupport

    public interface TestRegistry
extends ServiceManagerSupport, com.itko.lisa.net.LisaServerObject, com.itko.lisa.coordinator.PersistentMap
    The TestRegistry interface is the service interface for all LISA Test Registry implementations. As there is only one, and it is rather sparse, this will be brief. TestRegistry is branded as DevCloudManager (DCM) as of LISA 5.1

    In an effort to provide a very easy mechanism by which to both globally collect all the test servers that are available to stage tests, and a point upon which to build useful tracking/usage applications, the LISA Registry was born.

    This is the highest level of the test staging architecture. Across an entire logic network of testing systems, only one of these must be running. Others can be running, but the existence of the other would constitute another logical network of test servers.

    This is a daemon or service that provides a lookup service for LISA Coordinator Servers. Coordinator Servers construct Coordinators to run test cases. Further, this LISA Registry interface's single implementation, the TestRegistryImpl, will monitor the health of Coordinator Servers and remove those that are no longer responsive.

    A DCM has one or more Labs associated with it. There is always the Default lab which is a set of Coordinator servers, Simulator Servers, and VSE servers. The 'lab' may well be as simple as three processes running on a developer laptop or as complicated as an auto-scaling set of virtual machines in a public or private cloud.

    Naming In general, where the API has a named server in the method signature, you can pass a qualified name. A qualified name is of the form serverName@labName, for example Sim1@perfLab, Coordinator@funcLab, VSE@devLab. If there is no '@' in the name the Default lab is implied. The Default lab is always called Default and is always available.

    Names of services can be in the simple form, eg 'Coordinator' or in fully qualified for, eg tcp://machine.domain:port/name. If they are in the simple form, the DCM will return the first matching server name regardless of the protocol, machine name or port. So, it's theoretically possible to have two simulators, both called MySim but on different hosts: tcp://192.168.0.1:2014/MySim and tcp://192.168.0.1:2014/MySim. They both belong to a lab called PerfLab.

    If you called getSimulator("MySim@PerfLab") you would get back one of the simulators, which one however is undefined. The order might be round robin, or based on the simulator load profile and you get the one doing the least work, just don't rely on this behavior staying constant across LISA releases.

    If you called getCoordinatorServer(String) and passed null or empty string, you would get a random coordinator server from the Default lab. If you called getCoordinatorServer("@PerfLab") you would get a random coordServer from the PerfLab lab. If you called getCoordinatorServer("MyCS@PerfLab") you would get the 'MyCS' coordServer from the PerfLab lab (if there *is* a coordServer with that name, if there isn't you'd get a RemoteException. These examples hold true for getSimulator(String) and getVirtualServiceEnvironment(String). If you really want to fully qualify the name you could pass "tcp://some.machine.com:2014/MySuperFastSimulator@SomeLab"

    See Also:
    CoordinatorServer, Coordinator

        This method will work with all known simulators to get the given number of instances placed on the running Simulators The default implementation of the TestRegistry does not attempt to atomically stage tests, it would be too expensive.
